2 - Introduction¶

We are all passionate about the NBA and this data set has a variety of different information across comprehensive spreadsheets that are easy to understand but provide a challenge when analyzing.

Our topic is to predict what position an NBA player should play based on their physical attributes. We sought to discover how much of a correlation there was between physical stats such as height and bench press and position that existing NBA players play. Answering these questions is important because it provides valuable insights to three critical aspects of the NBA. For a player entering the league, this helps them decide where they fit in on a team and where they are likely to succeed. For a coach, it helps them know who to start at what position. Finally, for a General Manager of a team, this helps them know where a player will succeed and when they are drafting, they can draft a player who fills the position they are in need of.

3 - Data Curation¶

Kaggle Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/wyattowalsh/basketball
Description: The dataset contains NBA player combine statistics from 2000 onwards, including various physical attributes such as height, weight, wingspan, bench press performance, and position. This data offers insights into the physical profiles of players, providing a comprehensive view of their measurable athletic abilities. This kaggle page also included other datasets such as box scores and game results, but for the scope of this project we decided to focus on the NBA Draft Combine Statistics.

Conclusion

From the box plots orginally displayed, we can see that there is a good chance that position is related to bench press and body fat percentage. For example, we can see that a Center has a much higher bench press and body fat percentage than a point guard. To test this theory we did an ANOVA test with an alpha of 0.05, and we found that our p-value < alpha in both cases. This shows that there are significant differences in bench_press and body_fat_pct across different positions. To see which positions differ we conducted a post HOC test. From this we gathered that for bench press there are siginifcant differences in these positions: C-PG,C-SG,PF-PG,PF-SG,PF-SF. For body fat percentage there was a significant difference between all positions besides PG-SF, PG-SG, SG-SF. Lastly, we found that for each position there is not a strong linear relationship between bench press and body_fat_percentage.

Test 2

Height vs Center or not

Conducting a Z-Test based whether the height impacts whether a player can be a center

In [ ]:
import numpy as np
# First we extracted the data based on whether or not they are a center along with their height
center = df[df['position'].str.startswith('C')]
not_center = df[~df['position'].str.startswith('C')]

center_height = center['height_without_shoes']
not_center_height = not_center['height_without_shoes']
In [ ]:
# Now we calculated the means and standard deviations
center_mean_height = center_height.mean()
center_std_height = center_height.std()
center_count = len(center_height)


not_center_mean_height = not_center_height.mean()
not_center_std_height = not_center_height.std()
not_center_count = len(not_center_height)

print(center_mean_height)
print(center_std_height)
print(center_count)

print(not_center_mean_height)
print(not_center_std_height)
print(not_center_count)

In [ ]:
# Now find the z statistic and p value
z = (center_mean_height - not_center_mean_height) / np.sqrt((center_std_height ** 2 / center_count) + (not_center_std_height**2 / not_center_count))

p = 2 * (1 - stats.norm.cdf(abs(z)))
p
Out[ ]:
0.0

Since the p-value is less 0.05 we can confidently reject the null hypothesis, indicating that centers are taller than non-centers and there is a difference between the height of centers and non-centers

Conclusion

This test compared heights and whether or not a player is a center. This was a good way of seeing if height was truly as important to the playing center as usually perceived. By using a z test we could tell if whether or not a player was a center and height had a relationship and we could see if we could be truly confident in our conclusion. The test resulted in a p value of almost 0 (< 0.05) and as a result we rejected the null hypothesis, indicating that there was a strong relationship between centers and height.

We ran a chi squared test on the data comparing weight class and position. As seen from the chart above, the majority of players fall within the weight classes of 180-210 lbs and 210-240 lbs. The majority of power forwards (PF) are above 200 pounds whereas the majority of point guards are under 200 pounds. We can see that there are outliers with a few of the centers and power forwards being in the 270-300 and >300 weight classes. There is also 1 power forward under 180 pounds and 3 centers under 210 which are uncommon. Part 3 Starts Here: Analysis and Machine Learning¶

Goal: We are trying to predict the position of a player based on a variety of factors including height, weight, bench amount, and body fat percentage. We will construct a model that takes these factors into consideration

In [ ]:
strength_df = df[['position', 'height_without_shoes', 'weight', 'body_fat_pct', 'bench_press', 'wingspan', 'lane_agility_time', 'standing_reach', 'hand_length']]
strength_df = strength_df.dropna()
strength_df.drop('Unknown', inplace=True, errors='ignore')
strength_df['position'] = strength_df['position'].apply(lambda x: 'PG' if x in ['PG', 'PG-SG'] else x)
strength_df['position'] = strength_df['position'].apply(lambda x: 'SG' if x in ['SG', 'SG-PG', 'SG-SF'] else x)
strength_df['position'] = strength_df['position'].apply(lambda x: 'SF' if x in ['SF', 'SF-SG', 'SF-PF'] else x)
strength_df['position'] = strength_df['position'].apply(lambda x: 'PF' if x in ['PF', 'PF-SF','PF-C'] else x)
strength_df['position'] = strength_df['position'].apply(lambda x: 'C' if x in ['C', 'C-PF'] else x)

features = strength_df[['height_without_shoes', 'weight', 'body_fat_pct', 'bench_press', 'wingspan', 'lane_agility_time', 'standing_reach']]
target = strength_df['position']

label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
target_encoded = label_encoder.fit_transform(target)


X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, target_encoded, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Scale the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)


models = {
    'KNN': KNeighborsClassifier(),
    'DecisionTree': DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42),
    'LogisticRegression': LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=42),
    'RandomForest': RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
}

# Train and evaluate each model
for model_name, model in models.items():
    print(f"Training {model_name}...")
    model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
    print(f"Accuracy for {model_name}: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)}")
    print(f"Classification Report for {model_name}:\n{classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=label_encoder.classes_)}\n")

7 - Insights and Conclusions¶

Insight and Policy Decisions

Based on our analysis and modeling, we can make the following conclusions and recommendations:

  1. Position-Specific Insights: Centers are significantly taller and stronger, while Guards exhibit greater agility and lower body fat percentages. These physical distinctions highlight the role-specific demands in basketball.

  2. Predictive Accuracy: Machine learning models, particularly Random Forest, demonstrated high accuracy in predicting player positions based on physical attributes, offering a valuable tool for recruitment and talent evaluation.

  3. Strategic Recommendations: Recruitment strategies should focus on leveraging predictive models to streamline player selection processes and tailor training regimens to position-specific requirements, optimizing team performance.

  4. Explanation of accuracy of model: While the Logistic Regression accuracy is pretty high, being above 70%, it makes sense why it is not higher. In recent years basketball has been morphing into a more "positionless" game, meaning players do not always play one set position and can play more than one. Additionally teams now of days have been known to run lineups that do not necessarily follow the classic PG, SG, SF, PF, C convention where each position gets heavier and taller.

Future Directions: Expanding the dataset to include gameplay statistics and historical trends could provide deeper insights, enhancing recruitment and training strategies further. Additionally, integrating real-time player performance metrics could refine the predictive accuracy of our models. Overall, the results demonstrate that physical attributes are strong predictors of player positions, validating the importance of tailored analysis in sports data science. Future research could explore position-specific injury risks or optimize player fitness programs using advanced predictive analytics.
